i have a theory, if anyone <!here|@here> cares to hear it
ok well there’s a very specific failure that happens in the content resolver when the currently visible image is replaced by the background process
it goes like this. Let’s say your currently visible image has an ID of 10
Also, I think in theory this could effect non-legacy, but I don’t know what path they could get there on. fwiw. Weird stuff happens with databases sometimes.
you see it on your screen, you lock your phone
10 min later (but before the hour goes to the next hour) the background process runs to load new images
you download (for the sake of argument) 4 new images, their IDs are 2, 3, 4, 5
you unlock your phone
the system says “oh cool, give me the current image”
the SQL query that runs attempts to get the current image, but its not there AND theres not an image with a higher ID number (<--- this is the weird part)
the ContentResolver returns null
the code to handle not crashing _relies_ on that not returning null
ooooooh
so what we’d been fixing thus far
was the assumption that the bitmaps were blowing up
